44. Global vs local variables
A local variable is declared inside a function and can only be accessed within that function. 
A global variable is declared outside all functions and can be accessed throughout the program.
local: def add():
            x=10
global: x=10
        def add():
             print(x)

# This is a GLOBAL variable
global_msg = "I can be seen everywhere!"
def my_function():
    # This is a LOCAL variable
    local_msg = "I only exist inside this function!"
    print(local_msg)  # Works fine
    print(global_msg) # Works fine because it is global
my_function()
# Trying to access the variables outside the function:
print(global_msg)     # Works fine
print(local_msg)      # ERROR: NameError: name 'local_msg' is not defined

45. global keyword
The global keyword allows a function to modify a global variable instead of creating a local variable with the same name.
Also we can make the changes of global variable inside the func
count = 10
def update():
    global count
    count = 20
update()
print(count)  #20

